The correct mindset is to declare from the start you are a participant but that you will try to write of this place you have found and participated on as objectively as possible, both on a descriptive way and on what constitutes its building blocks, on a interaction basis, how it functions, what fuels it, so on. If you say this without meaning it (aka, lie about this statement), you might as well not try and write about this at all because if you are writing to find structures and data points, you should be trying to be detached and analytical.

The linguistics? Basically what I just wrote in this kind of style. You don't have to be this dry, god fucking knows I usually ain't, but when it comes to being effective in this kind of "essay", the real key is to try hard or just go home, because being frank there's a lot of meandering treatises in academia and otherwise which basically can be considered palimpsests. They aren't incisive, or really that insightful, and they write and rewrite themselves in the quest for a point.

Structure your thoughts, classify them, try and be objective and clear and you'll produce something better. Not guaranteed to get you a pulitzer or anything, you're writing about a trash general after all, even if quite a unique one.
